ght spans and with honest tone, but the requisition I traced bent it toward harm, because the purchase order asked for curvature that no sane brace would demand. I traced the requisition to Danka Suth, and when I went to ask questions, he smiled like a rigger proud of a perfect splice and my stomach went cold because I saw Riverfoot grit on his boot and eel-skin shine in his purse. A purse with eel-skin silver paid for a quiet stamp sat warm in his pocket, so I tried to tear the page and run, but they tied me like a bundle with a rafter’s knot I’d admire on any other day and kicked me into the fungus to let the beds remember me as a lost footstep rather than a living voice.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mira Olt\", \"lines\": \"Spore-light will hide her while we fetch a litter, and the beds here are old friends that know how to cradle what must be kept still without smothering breath. I’ll keep the midges off with peat smoke and a prayer to the slow breakers of fever, and I’ll cool her brow with drip-water so she feels a sky instead of a grave. Go, paladin, take the path of small lights and soft boots, and I will guard the woman’s spine with the same care I use with my own mother’s bones. The rafter knots on her skin smell like the Chainhouse at shift-change, and the brine in her boot seams tastes of the lower locks where eel-skin coins are counted in shadow. I’ll call two keepers and a Vigil clerk to witness what we lift and what we leave, so no mouth will successfully claim we trampled truth to hurry hope.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Thia Mol\", \"lines\": \"My lantern will draw you by three pulses and a moth-wing flourish down to the right rope, and if you keep your shoulders low and your heart steady, the Gardens will think you one of ours and not fuss when you pass. We’ve seen eel-skin shine in places it shouldn’t, and we’ve heard cable-song turn sour where happy work once sang, and that tells me a money-hand wants the city to dance on a frayed cord. Follow me 